    en: "Before signing a lease, every NY tenant has the right to a written disclosure of the building's smoking policy. The rule is in NY Real Property Law section 235-h, added in 2018. The disclosure must clearly say where smoking is allowed and where it is not — apartments, balconies, common areas, hallways, lobbies, courtyards, and any other location. The disclosure must also cover vaping and electronic cigarettes. Many large landlords adopt building-wide smoke-free policies; some allow smoking in apartments only. The disclosure helps tenants who are sensitive to smoke choose a building that matches their needs and gives them notice of what they can complain about later. The disclosure is in the lease or attached to it. Failure to provide the disclosure is a violation that can support tenant remedies for misrepresentation."
